{
  "doc_id": "25778",
  "text": "Antioxidants, metabolites of many plants, are found in a ubiquitous way in food, especially in vegetables, and they are one of the most important groups of natural compounds [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . They have anti-microbial and anticarcinogenic effects and above all a high antioxidant activity, demonstrated in vivo and in vitro experiments [CITATION_3] . In addition, their possible effects against cardiovascular diseases and neurodegenerative disorders have recently been demonstrated [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Considered as \"molecular markers\" of food quality, many articles are published every year about their determination. Some new antioxidant determination methods involve the use of NMNPs in two areas: the phenolic compound (principal class of antioxidant) determination and the antioxidant activity assays.",
